            <div type="typology">
               <head>Typology (Local)</head>
               <p rend="typology" xml:space="preserve">West (Maghreb) › Tunisia › North Western Tunisia</p>
               <p>Bedouin-type dialect</p>
            </div>
            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">Teboursouk constitutes a town and municipality in the Beja governorate. The Romans founded the ancient town Thubursicum Bure there, of which the modern town takes its name, but it was not until the Byzantine era that it gained importance and was turned into a fortress, the remains of which can still be seen today, surrounding partially the old city (<hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">m</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">d</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">ī</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">na</hi>). As the Arabic town was built on top of the ancient one, fountains from the Roman era can still be found in the houses. Only a few kilometres away, there are the ruins of the Roman Thugga (modern <seg type="comment" xml:id="seg0"><ref target="comment0" type="noteAnchor">Dougga</ref></seg>). </p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Due to the constant migration movements the town witnessed during the centuries, the dialect of Teboursouk was influenced by many different sources. According to locals, the town used to be home to several minorities like Jews, French, Andalusians, Italians, Maltese and Bulgarians.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Teboursouk is surrounded by olive groves, and among the main crops grown around the city are pomegranates, wheat and leguminosae. As there is no industry employing youth, agriculture and construction remain the main fields of work. As in other parts of Tunisia, traditional handicrafts are disappearing as the art is no longer transmitted to the new generations. Since there used to be no higher education in Teboursouk itself, students had to go to the capital or other Tunisian cities, where many changed their dialect from speaking with <hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">gǟ</hi> to using urban <hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">qā</hi>. Originally, however, Teboursoukians are known to speak with <hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">gǟ</hi>.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p xml:space="preserve">To the best of our knowledge hitherto no research has been done on the dialect of Testour, however this dialect is linguistically investigated within the TUNOCENT project.</p>
            </div>
